Obstructive sleep apnea (OSA) is a common sleep-related breathing disorder characterized by repetitive episodes of apnea or reduced inspiratory airflow due to upper airway obstruction during sleep. Patients with OSA are often obese and have an increased prevalence of numerous other cardiovascular risk factors, including hypertension and type 2 diabetes.
.
Obstructive sleep apnea is common among patients with resistant hypertension who are referred for sleep studies. In three series of patients with resistant hypertension who were referred for sleep studies, significant obstructive sleep apnea was detected in 71 to 85 percent and, in one, was significantly more common than in patients with controlled hypertension (71 versus 38 percent, adjusted odds ratio 4.8, 95% CI 2.0-11.7) . The severity of sleep apnea correlates with the severity of hypertension, and both the incidence and severity of sleep apnea were greater in men than women As an example, a prospective epidemiologic cohort study of 709 subjects estimated that patients with mild OSA (apnea hypopnea index [AHI] of 5 to 15 events per hour of sleep) had twice the risk of newly identified incident systemic hypertension, compared with those with an AHI of 0 (adjusted odds ratio 2.03, 95% CI 1.29-3.17), while subjects with an AHI of ≥15 events per hour of sleep had nearly three times the risk (adjusted odds ratio 2.89, 95% CI 1.46-5.64).
.

Post de @drmartinezclark -  La hipertensión resistente se definió en la declaración científica de la Asociación Americana del Corazón de 2008 y en las directrices de 2013 de las Sociedades Europeas de Hipertensión y Cardiología (ESH / ESC) como presión arterial que permanece por encima de la meta a pesar del uso concurrente de tres agentes anti-hipertensivos de diferentes clases. Los pacientes cuya presión arterial se controla con cuatro o más medicamentos deben considerarse como pacientes con hipertensión resistente.
.
¿Por qué es esto importante?
La hipertensión resistente, se asocia a menudo con una causa identificable de la hipertensión (hipertensión secundaria) la hipertensión secundaria se debe diagnosticar para controlar la presión arterial.
Por ejemplo, de los 1416 pacientes con hipertensión resistente que participaron en la denervación renal para la prueba de hipertensión resistente (DENERHTN), 709 (50%) fueron excluidos del tratamiento porque se identificó una causa secundaria de hipertensión. Las causas más comunes de la hipertensión secundaria son el aldosteronismo primario y la estenosis de la arteria renal, la enfermedad renal crónica y la apnea obstructiva del sueño. Las causas menos comunes incluyen feocromocitoma, síndrome de Cushing y coartación aórtica.
.

Prevent. Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV prevention option for people who don’t have HIV but who are at risk of becoming infected. PrEP involves taking a specific HIV medicine every day. PrEP should be combined with other prevention options, such as condoms. The best way to #Prevent is to talk to medical professionals, and trusted friends in a safe place. Don't be afraid to ask questions! Communication is KEY! We have the ability to end the stigma, and prevent HIV/AIDS in the future. Go to @aidsgov for more information. ❤️
